This HTML module successfully provides an engaging and interactive way for users to learn about linked lists.

Below is a self-contained interactive HTML page that provides an in-depth exploration of Hash Tables. This design focuses on clarity, interactivity, and responsiveness, emphasizing user engagement and learning.

### HTML Code

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Hash Table</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }

        .container {
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: auto;
            padding: 24px;
            background-color: #ffffff;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }

        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #333333;
        }

        p {
            color: #666666;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }

        #hashTableContainer {
            display: flex;
            flex-wrap: wrap;
            justify-content: space-between;
            margin: 20px 0;
            border: 2px dashed #ccc;
            padding: 16px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }

        .hashCell {
            width: calc(20% - 36px);
            margin: 8px;
            padding: 16px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 8px;
            background-color: #ffffff;
            text-align: center;
            transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
        }

        .hashCell:hover {
            background-color: #e6f7ff;
        }

        .inputSection {
            margin: 20px 0;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
        }

        input[type="text"] {
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 4px;
            width: 200px;
            margin-right: 8px;
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 16px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
        }

        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }

        #outputMessage {
            margin-top: 20px;
            color: #FF0000;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
    <h1>Interactive Hash Table</h1>
    <p>
        Welcome to the interactive hash table demonstration. A hash table is a data structure 
        that stores key-value pairs, allowing for fast retrieval.
    </p>
    <p>
        In this module, you will learn how hash tables work by inserting values, 
        observing collisions, and understanding how the hash function distributes keys.
    </p>

    <div id="hashTableContainer"></div>

    <div class="inputSection">
        <input type="text" id="inputKey" placeholder="Enter a key..." />
        <button id="insertButton">Insert</button>
    </div>

    <div id="outputMessage"></div>
</div>

<script>
    const hashTable = [];
    const tableSize = 8; // Size of the hash table

    // Initialize the hash table cells
    const tableContainer = document.getElementById('hashTableContainer');
    for (let i = 0; i < tableSize; i++) {
        const cell = document.createElement('div');
        cell.className = 'hashCell';
        cell.id = 'cell-' + i;
        cell.innerHTML = `<strong>${i}</strong><br />-`;
        hashTable.push(null);
        tableContainer.appendChild(cell);
    }

    // Hash function to determine index based on key
    function hashFunction(key) {
        return key.length % tableSize;
    }

    // Update visual representation of hash table
    function updateHashTable() {
        for (let i = 0; i < tableSize; i++) {
            const cell = document.getElementById('cell-' + i);
            cell.innerHTML = `<strong>${i}</strong><br />${hashTable[i] || '-'}`;
        }
    }

    // Insert key into hash table
    document.getElementById('insertButton').addEventListener('click', () => {
        const inputKey = document.getElementById('inputKey').value;
        if (!inputKey) {
            document.getElementById('outputMessage').innerText = "Please enter a key.";
            return;
        }
        const index = hashFunction(inputKey);
        if (hashTable[index] !== null) {
            document.getElementById('outputMessage').innerText = 
                `Collision! Key "${inputKey}" added to index ${index}.`;
        } else {
            document.getElementById('outputMessage').innerText = 
                `Key "${inputKey}" added at index ${index}.`;
        }
        hashTable[index] = inputKey; // Add key to the hash table
        updateHashTable(); // Update the visual representation
        document.getElementById('inputKey').value = ''; // Clear input
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of Design Sections

1. **Concept Title:** The title "Interactive Hash Table" concisely conveys the module's purpose.

2. **Learning Objective:** Users will understand how a hash table functions, how keys are stored, and what collisions are in this context.

3. **Interaction Design:** 
   - Users can type a key into the input field and click the "Insert" button to add it to the hash table.
   - If a collision occurs (when trying to insert a key into an already occupied index), users receive feedback indicating the collision.
   - The hash table visually updates to reflect the current state after each insertion.

4. **Layout Description:** 
   - The layout centers around a clean white container against a light gray background, providing focus. 
   - The hash table is organized as a flexible grid allowing users to see all cells simultaneously.
   - Ample spacing (24px margins and 16px between elements) maintains clarity and prevents overcrowding. 
   - The use of simple, interactive elements ensures user engagement, while responsive design techniques accommodate various screen sizes, allowing for an optimal experience across devices. 

This interactive HTML page remains self-contained and does not rely on external libraries or assets, facilitating easy deployment and learning engagement.

Here's a design plan for a high-quality interactive HTML page focused on teaching the concept of a Deque (Double-Ended Queue). The interactive module will enable users to visualize how a deque operates through user interactions.

### Interactive HTML Page Design Plan: Deque

#### Concept Title:
**Understanding Deques: The Double-Ended Queue**

#### Learning Objective:
Users will understand how a deque allows insertion and deletion of elements from both ends and visualize these operations interactively.

#### Interaction Design:
1. **Basic Structure:**
   - A visual representation of the deque using a horizontal bar (an array).
   - Users can interact by adding or removing elements from either end of the deque using buttons.

2. **User Interactions:**
   - **Buttons:** Users can click on “Add to Front”, “Add to Back”, “Remove from Front”, and “Remove from Back”.
   - **Dynamic Updates:** Each button click will add or remove items from the deque. The animations will visually represent these changes in real-time.
   - **Input Field:** Users can type an element in an input box that will be added to the deque.

3. **Feedback and Animation:**
   - Elements will "slide" in and out as they are added or removed.
   - Color changes will indicate successful operations (green for success, red for failure if trying to remove from an empty deque).
   - Display a message under the deque to show the current state of the deque after each operation.

#### Layout Description:
- **Viewport Structure:** The layout will maintain a centered structure with appropriate margins.
- **Top Section:** 
  - **Title**: Centered, bold font representing the concept title.

- **Middle Section:**
  - **Input Box**: Text input field (placeholder: "Enter value") left-aligned.
  - **Buttons**: 
    - Four buttons labeled accordingly, arranged in a row with minimum spacing of 16px between them.
  - **Deque Visualization**: A horizontal bar representing the deque, with currently added elements displayed as blocks inside this bar.

- **Bottom Section:**
  - **Status Message**: A small area below the deque visualization to display the state of the deque.

- **Margins and Spacing:** 
  - The entire layout will maintain a safe area of 24px on all sides and 16px between elements for clarity and focus.

### Implementation in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Deque</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
            padding: 24px;
        }
        h1 {
            margin-bottom: 24px;
        }
        #deque {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            border: 2px solid #ccc;
            width: 80%;
            max-width: 600px;
            height: 50px;
            background-color: white;
            margin-bottom: 16px;
            position: relative;
        }
        .element {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            margin: 0 4px;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            transition: translate 0.5s;
        }
        input {
            margin-right: 16px;
            padding: 10px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            margin: 0 8px;
            cursor: pointer;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        #status {
            margin-top: 16px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Understanding Deques: The Double-Ended Queue</h1>

    <div id="deque"></div>

    <input type="text" id="inputElement" placeholder="Enter value">
    <button onclick="addToFront()">Add to Front</button>
    <button onclick="addToBack()">Add to Back</button>
    <button onclick="removeFromFront()">Remove from Front</button>
    <button onclick="removeFromBack()">Remove from Back</button>

    <div id="status"></div>

    <script>
        let deque = [];

        function updateDequeDisplay() {
            const dequeElement = document.getElementById('deque');
            dequeElement.innerHTML = '';
            deque.forEach(element => {
                const div = document.createElement('div');
                div.className = 'element';
                div.textContent = element;
                dequeElement.appendChild(div);
            });
            document.getElementById('status').textContent = `Current Deque: [${deque.join(', ')}]`;
        }

        function addToFront() {
            const input = document.getElementById('inputElement').value;
            if (input) {
                deque.unshift(input);
                updateDequeDisplay();
                document.getElementById('inputElement').value = '';
            }
        }

        function addToBack() {
            const input = document.getElementById('inputElement').value;
            if (input) {
                deque.push(input);
                updateDequeDisplay();
                document.getElementById('inputElement').value = '';
            }
        }

        function removeFromFront() {
            if (deque.length > 0) {
                deque.shift();
                updateDequeDisplay();
            } else {
                document.getElementById('status').textContent = 'Deque is empty. Cannot remove from front.';
            }
        }

        function removeFromBack() {
            if (deque.length > 0) {
                deque.pop();
                updateDequeDisplay();
            } else {
                document.getElementById('status').textContent = 'Deque is empty. Cannot remove from back.';
            }
        }
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Code:
1. **HTML Structure:** 
   - The body contains a title, input field, buttons, a visualization of the deque, and status notifications.

2. **CSS Styles:**
   - Styles ensure clarity and responsiveness with flexbox layout. Each element is styled to ensure it is visually distinct and provides visual feedback.

3. **JavaScript Functionality:**
   - The script maintains an array as the deque and updates it based on user interaction. It dynamically generates the visual representation of the deque in response to actions.

This interactive page provides a hands-on approach for users to learn about a deque and reinforces learning through immediate feedback and visual representation.

Here's a detailed design plan for an interactive HTML module that explores the concept of a Queue data structure. 

### Interactive HTML Module: Queue

#### Concept Title:
**Understanding Queues: A Visual Exploration**

#### Learning Objective:
Users should understand the concept of a Queue as a data structure, its First-In-First-Out (FIFO) characteristic, and the basic operations such as enqueue (adding an item) and dequeue (removing an item).

#### Interaction Design:
1. **Initial State**: The user sees an empty Queue visual representation (a horizontal list with an input box and two buttons - "Enqueue" and "Dequeue").

2. **User Actions**:
   - **Enqueue**: Users can type a number into an input box and click the "Enqueue" button. 
     - **Feedback**: The number is added to the end of the queue with a smooth slide-in animation from the right. The queue visually stretches to accommodate the new item.
   - **Dequeue**: Users click the "Dequeue" button to remove the first item from the queue.
     - **Feedback**: The first item in the queue fades out and slides to the left before disappearing, while the next item moves into position.

3. **Data Visualization**: Both enqueue and dequeue operations will animate the items in the queue to reinforce the FIFO nature visually (first item added is the first one removed).

4. **Accessibility**: Each button will have a text label, and users can interact using a keyboard (Enter to trigger actions).

#### Layout Description:
- **Viewport**: The entire module is contained within a responsive box.
- **Safe Area Margins**: 24px on all sides to ensure content does not touch edges.
- **Spacing Between Elements**: 16px between buttons and the input box, ensuring distinct separation.
- **Positioning**:
  - A header at the top with the title centered.
  - Directly beneath, an illustrative queue (a row of boxes) centered horizontally.
  - Below the queue, an input field for the number and the "Enqueue" and "Dequeue" buttons, centered.
- **Visual Clarity**: The use of colors will help distinguish the queue blocks, buttons, and background. Clear text labels enhance readability.

#### Self-Contained Example Implementation:

